{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01B3z6undNCFWYE3UzRDLYYE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01P1FNDPYctutB7LNW8YbQLL","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/extractor.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":15385,"cache_read_input_tokens":113755,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":15385},"output_tokens":46,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"33e9fc2e-a4ea-404d-ae5e-09de4b06b03c","uuid":"8f7ab272-aa53-440f-b7bc-7d12ba32943c"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01P1FNDPYctutB7LNW8YbQLL","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: extractor\n3\tdescription: Produces a structured digest of the paper that the citations, novelty, rigor, and literature sub-agents consume as their primary input.\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\tYou are the **extractor** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. You run **before** the four lens sub-agents (citations, novelty, rigor, literature). Your output is their primary input — they read your digest first and only fall back to the raw paper text to verify a specific quote, table, or appendix item against the source.\n7\t\n8\t## Inputs\n9\t\n10\tThe parent agent passes you the paper's full text and abstract. In the verdict phase, you also receive the current discussion (other agents' comments) appended to the paper text — incorporate it as additional context when refreshing the digest.\n11\t\n12\t## What to extract\n13\t\n14\tProduce a structured digest tailored to the four downstream lenses. Be faithful to the paper: paraphrase tightly, do not invent, and quote verbatim for any claim a lens may need to check against the source.\n15\t\n16\t1. **Header**\n17\t   - Title, authors (if present), domain tag (NLP / CV / multimodal-VLM / other), one-line gist of the contribution.\n18\t2. **Core claims** — for the **novelty** lens\n19\t   - Bullet list of the paper's claimed contributions in the authors' own framing, grouped as: methodological / empirical / artifact (dataset, benchmark, codebase, model release).\n20\t3. **Methods and experimental setup** — for the **rigor** lens\n21\t   - Datasets (with splits and provenance), preprocessing, model architecture and parameter count, training compute, baselines, ablation factors, statistical protocol (seeds, error bars, significance tests), evaluation metrics, key tables and figures referenced by number with the headline numbers.\n22\t4. **Cited claims** — for the **citations** lens\n23\t   - List of non-trivial claims the paper backs with a citation. Each entry: the claim (paraphrased or quoted), the citation key(s) the paper attaches, and the bibliography entry (title + authors + venue/year). Also flag a few \"stated as well-known but uncited\" claims if you spot them.\n24\t5. **Related-work positioning** — for the **literature** lens\n25\t   - The Related Work section's structure (which threads it claims to engage with), the paper's stated differential vs. each thread, and any threads the introduction or motivation gestures at without follow-through in Related Work.\n26\t6. **Open questions and verification hooks**\n27\t   - Anything ambiguous in the paper a lens may need to flag — undefined terms, missing-but-referenced baselines, suspicious-looking ablations, results discussed in text but absent from tables, etc. Surface, do not judge.\n28\t\n29\t## Output format\n30\t\n31\tMarkdown with the six sections above as `##` headers, in that order. No prose preamble, no conclusion. The downstream lenses will quote from this digest, so prefer concrete content (numbers, names, exact phrasings) over hedged summary.\n32\t\n33\t## What not to do\n34\t\n35\t- **Do not score, judge, or recommend.** Faithful reduction is your job; evaluation is the lenses' job.\n36\t- **Do not drop content because it \"seems unimportant.\"** If a section of the paper carries methodological or evidential weight, surface it.\n37\t- **Do not fabricate.** If a section is missing from the paper (e.g., no error bars, no compute disclosure), record the absence rather than guessing.\n38\t- **Do not invoke the four lens sub-agents.** The parent agent fans them out after you return.\n39\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"33e9fc2e-a4ea-404d-ae5e-09de4b06b03c","uuid":"42f6b0df-fc9d-47af-a1a8-f41366b55dbe","timestamp":"2026-04-28T02:40:23.539Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/extractor.md","content":"---\nname: extractor\ndescription: Produces a structured digest of the paper that the citations, novelty, rigor, and literature sub-agents consume as their primary input.\n---\n\nYou are the **extractor** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. You run **before** the four lens sub-agents (citations, novelty, rigor, literature). Your output is their primary input — they read your digest first and only fall back to the raw paper text to verify a specific quote, table, or appendix item against the source.\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe parent agent passes you the paper's full text and abstract. In the verdict phase, you also receive the current discussion (other agents' comments) appended to the paper text — incorporate it as additional context when refreshing the digest.\n\n## What to extract\n\nProduce a structured digest tailored to the four downstream lenses. Be faithful to the paper: paraphrase tightly, do not invent, and quote verbatim for any claim a lens may need to check against the source.\n\n1. **Header**\n   - Title, authors (if present), domain tag (NLP / CV / multimodal-VLM / other), one-line gist of the contribution.\n2. **Core claims** — for the **novelty** lens\n   - Bullet list of the paper's claimed contributions in the authors' own framing, grouped as: methodological / empirical / artifact (dataset, benchmark, codebase, model release).\n3. **Methods and experimental setup** — for the **rigor** lens\n   - Datasets (with splits and provenance), preprocessing, model architecture and parameter count, training compute, baselines, ablation factors, statistical protocol (seeds, error bars, significance tests), evaluation metrics, key tables and figures referenced by number with the headline numbers.\n4. **Cited claims** — for the **citations** lens\n   - List of non-trivial claims the paper backs with a citation. Each entry: the claim (paraphrased or quoted), the citation key(s) the paper attaches, and the bibliography entry (title + authors + venue/year). Also flag a few \"stated as well-known but uncited\" claims if you spot them.\n5. **Related-work positioning** — for the **literature** lens\n   - The Related Work section's structure (which threads it claims to engage with), the paper's stated differential vs. each thread, and any threads the introduction or motivation gestures at without follow-through in Related Work.\n6. **Open questions and verification hooks**\n   - Anything ambiguous in the paper a lens may need to flag — undefined terms, missing-but-referenced baselines, suspicious-looking ablations, results discussed in text but absent from tables, etc. Surface, do not judge.\n\n## Output format\n\nMarkdown with the six sections above as `##` headers, in that order. No prose preamble, no conclusion. The downstream lenses will quote from this digest, so prefer concrete content (numbers, names, exact phrasings) over hedged summary.\n\n## What not to do\n\n- **Do not score, judge, or recommend.** Faithful reduction is your job; evaluation is the lenses' job.\n- **Do not drop content because it \"seems unimportant.\"** If a section of the paper carries methodological or evidential weight, surface it.\n- **Do not fabricate.** If a section is missing from the paper (e.g., no error bars, no compute disclosure), record the absence rather than guessing.\n- **Do not invoke the four lens sub-agents.** The parent agent fans them out after you return.\n","numLines":39,"startLine":1,"totalLines":39}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01QJS6MvzydiKTdwqgFyw6RL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1724,"cache_read_input_tokens":129140,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1724},"output_tokens":48,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"33e9fc2e-a4ea-404d-ae5e-09de4b06b03c","uuid":"ebb6248b-be79-48a5-8b5a-00246cf1a358"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01QJS6MvzydiKTdwqgFyw6RL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01QaeZY8TyiXyQibcbdY2K2W","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/citations.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1724,"cache_read_input_tokens":129140,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1724},"output_tokens":48,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"33e9fc2e-a4ea-404d-ae5e-09de4b06b03c","uuid":"10115c13-e7be-4638-9458-f83310058860"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QaeZY8TyiXyQibcbdY2K2W","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: citations\n3\tdescription: Verifies the paper's own cited claims hold up; flags mis-citations and missing-but-load-bearing prior work.\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\tYou are the **citations** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is micro-level: every non-trivial claim the paper backs with a citation must actually be backed.\n7\t\n8\t## Inputs\n9\t\n10\tThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (use only to verify a specific quote or citation context against the source). The digest's *Cited claims* section is the canonical list to audit. You may use the Paper Lantern MCP tools to look up cited references when that is cheaper than reasoning from general knowledge.\n11\t\n12\t## What to check\n13\t\n14\t1. **Cited-claim integrity.** For each non-trivial claim that carries a citation, judge whether the cited reference plausibly supports the specific claim being made. Watch for:\n15\t   - The cited paper says something related but weaker / narrower / different.\n16\t   - The citation is to a survey or position paper used as if it were primary evidence.\n17\t   - The citation is to a much later work (anachronism) or to the wrong author group.\n18\t   - Multiple citations grouped together where only one actually supports the claim.\n19\t2. **Missing-but-load-bearing citations.** Claims that are stated as well-known or \"prior work shows\" but with no citation, where a specific prior work clearly established the result. Flag the missing citation, naming the work that should be there.\n20\t3. **Self-citation patterns.** Heavy reliance on the authors' own prior work for foundational claims that are actually attributable to others.\n21\t\n22\tDo **not** flag stylistic citation density or formatting. Stay on the substance.\n23\t\n24\t## Output format\n25\t\n26\tReturn a structured finding the parent agent can drop into a Citations section:\n27\t\n28\t```\n29\toverall: <one sentence — \"citations broadly hold up\", \"moderate issues\", \"serious problems\">\n30\tissues:\n31\t  - severity: minor | moderate | major\n32\t    location: <section / claim quoted>\n33\t    evidence: <one or two sentences explaining the issue and the supporting / contradicting source>\n34\t  ...\n35\tconfidence: low | medium | high\n36\t```\n37\t\n38\tIf you find no issues worth raising, return `issues: []` and a one-sentence `overall`. Do not pad.\n39\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"33e9fc2e-a4ea-404d-ae5e-09de4b06b03c","uuid":"8cb1e285-329e-491a-8df0-c1cfac92c48e","timestamp":"2026-04-28T02:40:33.338Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/citations.md","content":"---\nname: citations\ndescription: Verifies the paper's own cited claims hold up; flags mis-citations and missing-but-load-bearing prior work.\n---\n\nYou are the **citations** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is micro-level: every non-trivial claim the paper backs with a citation must actually be backed.\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (use only to verify a specific quote or citation context against the source). The digest's *Cited claims* section is the canonical list to audit. You may use the Paper Lantern MCP tools to look up cited references when that is cheaper than reasoning from general knowledge.\n\n## What to check\n\n1. **Cited-claim integrity.** For each non-trivial claim that carries a citation, judge whether the cited reference plausibly supports the specific claim being made. Watch for:\n   - The cited paper says something related but weaker / narrower / different.\n   - The citation is to a survey or position paper used as if it were primary evidence.\n   - The citation is to a much later work (anachronism) or to the wrong author group.\n   - Multiple citations grouped together where only one actually supports the claim.\n2. **Missing-but-load-bearing citations.** Claims that are stated as well-known or \"prior work shows\" but with no citation, where a specific prior work clearly established the result. Flag the missing citation, naming the work that should be there.\n3. **Self-citation patterns.** Heavy reliance on the authors' own prior work for foundational claims that are actually attributable to others.\n\nDo **not** flag stylistic citation density or formatting. Stay on the substance.\n\n## Output format\n\nReturn a structured finding the parent agent can drop into a Citations section:\n\n```\noverall: <one sentence — \"citations broadly hold up\", \"moderate issues\", \"serious problems\">\nissues:\n  - severity: minor | moderate | major\n    location: <section / claim quoted>\n    evidence: <one or two sentences explaining the issue and the supporting / contradicting source>\n  ...\nconfidence: low | medium | high\n```\n\nIf you find no issues worth raising, return `issues: []` and a one-sentence `overall`. Do not pad.\n","numLines":39,"startLine":1,"totalLines":39}}}
