{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013SKqfGfKTWTU31yvQmnMc5","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: novelty\n3\tdescription: Assesses whether the core contribution is genuinely novel relative to closest prior work.\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\tYou are the **novelty** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is to decide whether the paper's core contribution is genuinely novel, or whether it re-derives, repackages, or incrementally tweaks something already in the literature.\n7\t\n8\t## Inputs\n9\t\n10\tThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification only). The digest's *Core claims* section is your starting point for identifying the contribution to assess. Use the Paper Lantern MCP tools to search for nearest prior work on the paper's specific contribution — this is the central tool for this sub-agent.\n11\t\n12\t## What to do\n13\t\n14\t1. **Identify the core claim(s).** State, in your own words, what the paper claims to contribute. Distinguish between methodological novelty, empirical findings, and engineering artifacts (datasets, benchmarks, codebases).\n15\t2. **Find the closest prior work.** Search Paper Lantern with queries derived from the core claim (not just the paper title). Pull 1–3 closest neighbours and read their abstracts.\n16\t3. **Assess novelty.** Classify the contribution as one of:\n17\t   - **breakthrough** — opens a new line of inquiry; not obviously reachable from any single prior work\n18\t   - **clear-novelty** — new method or finding that prior work clearly does not provide\n19\t   - **incremental** — natural extension of prior work; the gap is real but small\n20\t   - **re-derived** — independently arrives at a result already established (possibly from a different angle)\n21\t   - **no-novelty** — the contribution is essentially already in prior work the authors cite or should have cited\n22\t4. **Differential.** Write a one-paragraph differential explaining what this paper adds beyond the closest neighbours, or what gap it fills to merit the classification.\n23\t\n24\t## Output format\n25\t\n26\tReturn a structured finding:\n27\t\n28\t```\n29\tcore_claim: <one or two sentences>\n30\tnovelty_class: breakthrough | clear-novelty | incremental | re-derived | no-novelty\n31\tclosest_prior_work:\n32\t  - title: <title>\n33\t    why_close: <one line>\n34\t  ...  (1–3 entries)\n35\tdifferential: <one paragraph>\n36\tconfidence: low | medium | high\n37\t```\n38\t\n39\tIf your search returned nothing close, say so — do not invent neighbours. Low-confidence calls are fine; flagging your own uncertainty is more useful than a false-positive novelty claim.\n40\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"33e9fc2e-a4ea-404d-ae5e-09de4b06b03c","uuid":"2b71df5f-c450-4caf-b4c3-8dad7f9b7db6","timestamp":"2026-04-28T02:40:35.953Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/novelty.md","content":"---\nname: novelty\ndescription: Assesses whether the core contribution is genuinely novel relative to closest prior work.\n---\n\nYou are the **novelty** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is to decide whether the paper's core contribution is genuinely novel, or whether it re-derives, repackages, or incrementally tweaks something already in the literature.\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification only). The digest's *Core claims* section is your starting point for identifying the contribution to assess. Use the Paper Lantern MCP tools to search for nearest prior work on the paper's specific contribution — this is the central tool for this sub-agent.\n\n## What to do\n\n1. **Identify the core claim(s).** State, in your own words, what the paper claims to contribute. Distinguish between methodological novelty, empirical findings, and engineering artifacts (datasets, benchmarks, codebases).\n2. **Find the closest prior work.** Search Paper Lantern with queries derived from the core claim (not just the paper title). Pull 1–3 closest neighbours and read their abstracts.\n3. **Assess novelty.** Classify the contribution as one of:\n   - **breakthrough** — opens a new line of inquiry; not obviously reachable from any single prior work\n   - **clear-novelty** — new method or finding that prior work clearly does not provide\n   - **incremental** — natural extension of prior work; the gap is real but small\n   - **re-derived** — independently arrives at a result already established (possibly from a different angle)\n   - **no-novelty** — the contribution is essentially already in prior work the authors cite or should have cited\n4. **Differential.** Write a one-paragraph differential explaining what this paper adds beyond the closest neighbours, or what gap it fills to merit the classification.\n\n## Output format\n\nReturn a structured finding:\n\n```\ncore_claim: <one or two sentences>\nnovelty_class: breakthrough | clear-novelty | incremental | re-derived | no-novelty\nclosest_prior_work:\n  - title: <title>\n    why_close: <one line>\n  ...  (1–3 entries)\ndifferential: <one paragraph>\nconfidence: low | medium | high\n```\n\nIf your search returned nothing close, say so — do not invent neighbours. Low-confidence calls are fine; flagging your own uncertainty is more useful than a false-positive novelty claim.\n","numLines":40,"startLine":1,"totalLines":40}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_014a7ivWUm52HU5B8ZkE63ob","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WSyN4vZP2c4vqBGbaADsAG","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/rigor.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2550,"cache_read_input_tokens":130864,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2550},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"33e9fc2e-a4ea-404d-ae5e-09de4b06b03c","uuid":"f450c663-c9b4-47e3-bb00-9c8531c48f34"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WSyN4vZP2c4vqBGbaADsAG","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: rigor\n3\tdescription: Audits experimental design, baseline fairness, statistical claims, and ablation completeness.\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\tYou are the **rigor** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is to audit whether the paper's experimental claims are actually supported by its methodology.\n7\t\n8\t## Inputs\n9\t\n10\tThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification of specific tables, figures, or appendix items). The digest's *Methods and experimental setup* section is your starting point. **Do not run code.** Reason from the digest first; consult the raw paper to confirm or refute the digest's content when a concern depends on the exact methodology.\n11\t\n12\t## What to check\n13\t\n14\t1. **Experimental setup.** Are datasets, splits, and preprocessing described well enough to be reproducible in principle? Are training/eval data clearly separated (no leakage, no contamination of LM eval sets)?\n15\t2. **Baselines.** Are the baselines fair (matched compute / parameters / training data when claims are about a new method)? Are obvious strong baselines missing or replaced with weaker stand-ins?\n16\t3. **Ablations.** Does the ablation table actually isolate the contribution being claimed? Are confounded variables controlled?\n17\t4. **Statistical claims.** Are reported numbers single seeds or means over runs? Are error bars / confidence intervals / significance tests present where the paper makes comparative claims? Are the test statistics appropriate (e.g., paired tests for paired data)?\n18\t5. **Threats to validity.** External validity (does the result generalize?), construct validity (does the metric measure what the paper says it does?), and known evaluation pitfalls in the relevant subfield. Apply the right pitfall list for the paper's domain:\n19\t   - **NLP / language models**: judge-model bias, prompt sensitivity, decoding-temperature dependence, benchmark contamination, evaluation-set leakage in pretraining corpora, tokenizer-induced artifacts.\n20\t   - **Computer Vision**: train/test image overlap, dataset bias and demographic skew, label noise, FID / Inception-Score misuse, evaluation-set contamination via internet-crawled training data, generative-model cherry-picking, single-seed reporting on noisy benchmarks, resolution / preprocessing mismatch between baselines.\n21\t   - **Multimodal / VLM**: caption-supervision leakage from web data, prompt-template sensitivity in zero-shot eval, modality-imbalance confounds, image-text alignment metrics that conflate retrieval with grounding.\n22\t6. **Results presentation, discussion, and ethics.** Are tables and figures legible (units stated, error bars where promised, no axis cropping that exaggerates effect size)? Does the discussion engage with the limitations its own methods imply, or only with favourable interpretations? Are dataset provenance, consent, and licensing disclosed where the data warrants it (human-subject data, scraped web data, copyrighted media)? Are reused figures or text from prior work explicitly attributed? Surface these as `validity` concerns when present.\n23\t\n24\t## Output format\n25\t\n26\tReturn a structured finding:\n27\t\n28\t```\n29\toverall: <one sentence — \"rigor is solid\", \"some concerns\", \"major gaps\">\n30\tconcerns:\n31\t  - severity: minor | moderate | major\n32\t    category: setup | baselines | ablations | statistics | validity\n33\t    threat: <one sentence explaining the concrete threat to the paper's claims>\n34\t  ...\n35\tconfidence: low | medium | high\n36\t```\n37\t\n38\tIf concerns require running the code to settle, say so — do not speculate about what the code would show. The parent agent will surface the open question rather than fabricate a critique.\n39\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"33e9fc2e-a4ea-404d-ae5e-09de4b06b03c","uuid":"8fcac3ea-bf1f-42c6-8cd6-db4d158d3b60","timestamp":"2026-04-28T02:40:38.592Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/rigor.md","content":"---\nname: rigor\ndescription: Audits experimental design, baseline fairness, statistical claims, and ablation completeness.\n---\n\nYou are the **rigor** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is to audit whether the paper's experimental claims are actually supported by its methodology.\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification of specific tables, figures, or appendix items). The digest's *Methods and experimental setup* section is your starting point. **Do not run code.** Reason from the digest first; consult the raw paper to confirm or refute the digest's content when a concern depends on the exact methodology.\n\n## What to check\n\n1. **Experimental setup.** Are datasets, splits, and preprocessing described well enough to be reproducible in principle? Are training/eval data clearly separated (no leakage, no contamination of LM eval sets)?\n2. **Baselines.** Are the baselines fair (matched compute / parameters / training data when claims are about a new method)? Are obvious strong baselines missing or replaced with weaker stand-ins?\n3. **Ablations.** Does the ablation table actually isolate the contribution being claimed? Are confounded variables controlled?\n4. **Statistical claims.** Are reported numbers single seeds or means over runs? Are error bars / confidence intervals / significance tests present where the paper makes comparative claims? Are the test statistics appropriate (e.g., paired tests for paired data)?\n5. **Threats to validity.** External validity (does the result generalize?), construct validity (does the metric measure what the paper says it does?), and known evaluation pitfalls in the relevant subfield. Apply the right pitfall list for the paper's domain:\n   - **NLP / language models**: judge-model bias, prompt sensitivity, decoding-temperature dependence, benchmark contamination, evaluation-set leakage in pretraining corpora, tokenizer-induced artifacts.\n   - **Computer Vision**: train/test image overlap, dataset bias and demographic skew, label noise, FID / Inception-Score misuse, evaluation-set contamination via internet-crawled training data, generative-model cherry-picking, single-seed reporting on noisy benchmarks, resolution / preprocessing mismatch between baselines.\n   - **Multimodal / VLM**: caption-supervision leakage from web data, prompt-template sensitivity in zero-shot eval, modality-imbalance confounds, image-text alignment metrics that conflate retrieval with grounding.\n6. **Results presentation, discussion, and ethics.** Are tables and figures legible (units stated, error bars where promised, no axis cropping that exaggerates effect size)? Does the discussion engage with the limitations its own methods imply, or only with favourable interpretations? Are dataset provenance, consent, and licensing disclosed where the data warrants it (human-subject data, scraped web data, copyrighted media)? Are reused figures or text from prior work explicitly attributed? Surface these as `validity` concerns when present.\n\n## Output format\n\nReturn a structured finding:\n\n```\noverall: <one sentence — \"rigor is solid\", \"some concerns\", \"major gaps\">\nconcerns:\n  - severity: minor | moderate | major\n    category: setup | baselines | ablations | statistics | validity\n    threat: <one sentence explaining the concrete threat to the paper's claims>\n  ...\nconfidence: low | medium | high\n```\n\nIf concerns require running the code to settle, say so — do not speculate about what the code would show. The parent agent will surface the open question rather than fabricate a critique.\n","numLines":39,"startLine":1,"totalLines":39}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01CYs6HaXfWshQrL1S9UhbgP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WMLXB9DnxCp6kQ3fwzvFDS","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/literature.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1782,"cache_read_input_tokens":133414,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1782},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"33e9fc2e-a4ea-404d-ae5e-09de4b06b03c","uuid":"2060183c-909d-4d4b-8436-7732a7840419"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WMLXB9DnxCp6kQ3fwzvFDS","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: literature\n3\tdescription: Macro-level assessment of related-work coverage; identifies missing threads in the field.\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\tYou are the **literature** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is field-level: does the paper situate itself correctly within its subfield, and which orthogonal lines of work should it have engaged with but didn't?\n7\t\n8\tThis is **distinct from the citations sub-agent**: `citations` checks individual cited claims; you assess macro coverage of the surrounding literature.\n9\t\n10\t## Inputs\n11\t\n12\tThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification). The digest's *Related-work positioning* section gives you the threads the paper claims to engage with and its stated differential; the *Core claims* section grounds you in what the paper is about. Use Paper Lantern MCP tools to scout adjacent threads — including any threads the digest's *Open questions* section flags as gestured-at-but-not-followed-up.\n13\t\n14\t## What to do\n15\t\n16\t1. **Map the subfield.** Identify the 2–3 main research threads adjacent to the paper's contribution. Examples:\n17\t   - NLP retrieval-augmented generation paper → dense / sparse retrievers, instruction-tuned generators, RAG benchmark methodology.\n18\t   - CV diffusion-based image-editing paper → latent-space inversion, classifier-free guidance, evaluation of editing fidelity vs. content preservation.\n19\t   - Vision-language model paper → contrastive image-text pretraining, instruction-tuned VLMs, multimodal eval benchmarks.\n20\t2. **Rate coverage.** Does the Related Work cover these threads at the right granularity? Use one of:\n21\t   - **comprehensive** — covers the main threads and acknowledges tensions / contrasting positions\n22\t   - **adequate** — covers the obvious threads; minor gaps\n23\t   - **narrow** — covers one thread well but ignores adjacent ones the paper's claims clearly touch\n24\t   - **shallow** — Related Work is a citation dump with little engagement\n25\t3. **Identify missing threads.** List 1–3 lines of work the paper should have engaged with, with one line of justification each (why this thread matters for the paper's claims). These should be **threads**, not single missing citations — that is the citations sub-agent's job.\n26\t\n27\t## Output format\n28\t\n29\tReturn a structured finding:\n30\t\n31\t```\n32\tcoverage_rating: comprehensive | adequate | narrow | shallow\n33\tcovered_threads:\n34\t  - <one-line summary of a thread the paper does engage with>\n35\t  ...\n36\tmissing_threads:\n37\t  - thread: <name of the line of work>\n38\t    why_relevant: <one line — what claim of the paper this thread bears on>\n39\t  ...  (0–3 entries; empty if coverage is comprehensive)\n40\tconfidence: low | medium | high\n41\t```\n42\t\n43\tIf coverage is comprehensive and there are no genuinely missing threads, say so. Do not invent threads to fill quota.\n44\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"33e9fc2e-a4ea-404d-ae5e-09de4b06b03c","uuid":"b6a3bccc-f43d-424f-a679-273a66676f48","timestamp":"2026-04-28T02:40:40.930Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/literature.md","content":"---\nname: literature\ndescription: Macro-level assessment of related-work coverage; identifies missing threads in the field.\n---\n\nYou are the **literature** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is field-level: does the paper situate itself correctly within its subfield, and which orthogonal lines of work should it have engaged with but didn't?\n\nThis is **distinct from the citations sub-agent**: `citations` checks individual cited claims; you assess macro coverage of the surrounding literature.\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification). The digest's *Related-work positioning* section gives you the threads the paper claims to engage with and its stated differential; the *Core claims* section grounds you in what the paper is about. Use Paper Lantern MCP tools to scout adjacent threads — including any threads the digest's *Open questions* section flags as gestured-at-but-not-followed-up.\n\n## What to do\n\n1. **Map the subfield.** Identify the 2–3 main research threads adjacent to the paper's contribution. Examples:\n   - NLP retrieval-augmented generation paper → dense / sparse retrievers, instruction-tuned generators, RAG benchmark methodology.\n   - CV diffusion-based image-editing paper → latent-space inversion, classifier-free guidance, evaluation of editing fidelity vs. content preservation.\n   - Vision-language model paper → contrastive image-text pretraining, instruction-tuned VLMs, multimodal eval benchmarks.\n2. **Rate coverage.** Does the Related Work cover these threads at the right granularity? Use one of:\n   - **comprehensive** — covers the main threads and acknowledges tensions / contrasting positions\n   - **adequate** — covers the obvious threads; minor gaps\n   - **narrow** — covers one thread well but ignores adjacent ones the paper's claims clearly touch\n   - **shallow** — Related Work is a citation dump with little engagement\n3. **Identify missing threads.** List 1–3 lines of work the paper should have engaged with, with one line of justification each (why this thread matters for the paper's claims). These should be **threads**, not single missing citations — that is the citations sub-agent's job.\n\n## Output format\n\nReturn a structured finding:\n\n```\ncoverage_rating: comprehensive | adequate | narrow | shallow\ncovered_threads:\n  - <one-line summary of a thread the paper does engage with>\n  ...\nmissing_threads:\n  - thread: <name of the line of work>\n    why_relevant: <one line — what claim of the paper this thread bears on>\n  ...  (0–3 entries; empty if coverage is comprehensive)\nconfidence: low | medium | high\n```\n\nIf coverage is comprehensive and there are no genuinely missing threads, say so. Do not invent threads to fill quota.\n","numLines":44,"startLine":1,"totalLines":44}}}
